[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating test strategies**\n\nI’m considering adding a test that doesn't skip and catches SWTError related to platform failures, particularly if Windows is expected to succeed. However, on Linux, Display construction could fail due to UnsatisfiedLinkError. It might be necessary to catch Throwable around UI setup and return if the platform isn’t supported, akin to skipping. I'm questioning if that violates the no-skip rule. Using JUnit's OS check with `EnabledOnOs` could be a more graceful solution. The task states to refine tests to reach uncovered execution, so skipping might not be ideal.\n\n**Exploring integration issues**\n\nI'm trying to work out the support for the public field, which can be set, but maybe any limitations appear when it comes to Native since it seems to ignore some aspects. On Windows, when using `initFrame`, it incorporates WEmbeddedFrame and the results look good. I wonder if WEmbeddedFrame is also included in Native. It seems AWT support might be somewhat limited, so I'll need to consider that in my approach.\n\n**Evaluating dynamic class structure**\n\nI'm thinking it might be alright, but there’s this concern about the one-to-one mapping. It suggests a dynamic class should be in its own file. Using a generic placeholder feels a bit off since it's not dynamic. I could update the placeholder to public and maybe a no-op, but that may not be necessary. I think about whether all top-level test classes should be public or if we should also change existing ones to public.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0253e81474ed6bf8016a1e9b3ac9e08194a52f5a684143ba3d\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqHptY-EHXUbFlW1Mu8FtWx-xOaZJSAdYHrOr1f7fi6tYvCKhch-BFp9mji_MogZy-K7Rd8pNJVwXUX4HZLANNpr_qvqVgCkaBFNnsi5riJ6c7bxDfM0xpTpdmFu2hOc-fOQPBMIT6DGarbcxU66ysO-7iTItVQ32zwatfDaH908DhDZaqUldoVfVHcyOgofZDYrxhH9TMNWA57QMHrdpAbjEs25R6Wols6g